msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr "摘要"

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:9
msgid ""
"This RFC proposes the addition of two macros to the global prelude, `eprint!"
"` and `eprintln!`.  These are exactly the same as `print!` and `println!`, "
"respectively, except that they write to standard error instead of standard "
"output."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:14
msgid ""
"An [implementation](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/39229/files) "
"already exists."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:16
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr "動機"

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:19
msgid ""
"This proposal will improve the ergonomics of the Rust language for "
"development of command-line tools and \"back end\" / \"computational "
"kernel\" programs.  Such programs need to maintain a distinction between "
"their _primary output_, which will be fed to the next element in a "
"computational \"pipeline\", and their _status reports_, which should go "
"directly to the user.  Conventionally, standard output should receive the "
"primary output and standard error should receive status reports."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:28
msgid ""
"At present, writing text to standard output is very easy, using the "
"`print(ln)!` macros, but writing text to standard error is significantly "
"more work: compare"
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:32
msgid ""
"    println!(\"out of cheese error: {}\", 42);\n"
"    writeln!(stderr(), \"out of cheese error: {}\", 42).unwrap();\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:35
msgid ""
"The latter may also require the addition of `use std::io::stderr` and/or "
"`use std::io::Write;` to the top of the file."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:38
msgid ""
"Because writing to stderr is more work, and requires introduction of more "
"concepts, all of the tutorial documentation for the language uses `println!` "
"for error messages, which teaches bad habits."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:42
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr "詳細設計"

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:45
msgid ""
"Two macros will be added to the global prelude.  `eprint!` is exactly the "
"same as `print!`, and `eprintln!` is exactly the same as `println!`, except "
"that both of them write to standard error instead of standard output.  "
"\"Standard error\" is defined as \"the same place where `panic!` writes "
"messages.\"  In particular, using `set_panic` to change where panic messages "
"go will also affect `eprint!` and `eprintln!`."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:53
msgid ""
"Previous discussion has converged on agreement that both these macros will "
"be useful, but has not arrived at a consensus about their names. An "
"executive decision is necessary.  It is the author's opinion that `eprint!` "
"and `eprintln!` have the strongest case in their favor, being (a) almost as "
"short as `print!` and `println!`, (b) still visibly different from them, and "
"(c) the names chosen by several third-party crate authors who implemented "
"these macros themselves for internal use."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:62
msgid "How We Teach This"
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:65
msgid ""
"We will need to add text to the reference manual, and especially to the "
"tutorials, explaining the difference between \"primary output\" and \"status "
"reports\", so that programmers know when to use `println!` and when to use "
"`eprintln!`.  All of the existing examples and tutorials should be checked "
"over for cases where `println!` is being used for a status report, and all "
"such cases should be changed to use `eprintln!` instead; similarly for "
"`print!`."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:73
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:76
msgid ""
"The usual drawbacks of adding macros to the prelude apply.  In this case, I "
"think the most significant concern is to choose names that are unlikely to "
"conflict with existing library crates' _exported_ macros.  (Conversely, "
"_internal_ macros with the same names and semantics demonstrate that the "
"names chosen are appropriate.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:82
msgid ""
"The names `eprintln!` and `eprint!` are terse, differing only in a single "
"letter from `println!` and `print!`, and it's not obvious at a glance what "
"the leading `e` means.  (\"This is too cryptic\" is the single most "
"frequently heard complaint from people who don't like `eprintln!`.)  "
"However, once you do know what it means it is reasonably memorable, and "
"anyone who is already familiar with stdout versus stderr is very likely to "
"guess correctly what it means."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:90
msgid ""
"There is an increased teaching burden---but that's the wrong way to look at "
"it.  The Book and the reference manual _should have_ been teaching the "
"difference between \"primary output\" and \"status reports\" all along.  "
"This is something programmers already need to know in order to write "
"programs that fit well into the larger ecosystem.  Any documentation that "
"might be a new programmer's first exposure to the concept of \"standard "
"output\" has a duty to explain that there is also \"standard error\", and "
"when you should use which."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:99
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr "替代方案"

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:102
msgid ""
"It would be inappropriate to introduce printing-to-stderr macros whose "
"behavior did not exactly parallel the existing printing-to-stdout macros; I "
"will not discuss that possibility further."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:106
msgid ""
"We could provide only `eprintln!`, omitting the no-newline variant. Most "
"_error_ messages should be one or more complete lines, so it's not obvious "
"that we need `eprint!`.  However, standard error is also the appropriate "
"place to send _progress_ messages, and it is common to want to print partial "
"lines in progress messages, as this is a natural way to express \"a time-"
"consuming computation is running\". [For example](https://github.com/rust-"
"lang/rfcs/pull/1869#issuecomment-274609380):"
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:122
msgid ""
"We could choose different names.  Quite a few other possibilities have been "
"suggested in the [pre-RFC](https://internals.rust-lang.org/t/extremely-pre-"
"rfc-eprintln/4635/10) and [RFC](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/1869) "
"discussions; they fall into three broad classes:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:126
msgid ""
"`error(ln)!` and `err(ln)!` are ruled out as too likely to collide with "
"third-party crates.  `error!` in particular is already taken by the [`log` "
"crate](https://crates.io/crates/log)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:130
msgid ""
"`println_err!`, `printlnerr!`, `errprintln!`, and several other variants on "
"this theme are less terse, but also more typing.  It is the author's "
"personal opinion that minimizing additional typing here is a Good Thing.  "
"People do live with `fprintf(stderr, ...)` in C, but on the other hand there "
"is a lot of sloppy C out there that sends its error messages to stdout.  I "
"want to minimize the friction in _using_ `eprintln!` once you already know "
"what it means."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:138
msgid ""
"It is also highly desirable to put the distinguishing label at the "
"_beginning_ of the macro name, as this makes the difference stand out more "
"when skimming code."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:142
msgid ""
"`aprintln!`, `dprintln!`, `uprintln!`, `println2!`, etc. are not less "
"cryptic than `eprintln!`, and the official name of standard I/O stream 2 is "
"\"standard _error_\", even though it's not just for errors, so `e` is the "
"best choice."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:147
msgid ""
"Finally, we could think of some way to improve the ergonomics of `writeln!` "
"so that we don't need the new macros at all.  There are four fundamental "
"problems with that, though:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:151
msgid ""
"`writeln!(stderr(), ...)` is always going to be more typing than `eprintln!"
"(...)`.  (Again, people do live with `fprintf(stderr, ...)` in C, but again, "
"minimizing usage friction is highly desirable.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:156
msgid ""
"On a similar note, use of `writeln!` requires `use std::io::Write`, in "
"contrast to C where `#include <stdio.h>` gets you both `printf` and "
"`fprintf`.  I am not sure how often this would be the _only_ use of `writeln!"
"` in complex programs, however."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:161
msgid ""
"`writeln!` returns a Result, which must be consumed; this is appropriate for "
"the intended core uses of `writeln!`, but means tacking `.unwrap()` on the "
"end of every use to print diagnostics (if printing diagnostics fails, it is "
"almost always the case that there's nothing more sensible to do than crash)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1869-eprintln.md:167
msgid ""
"`writeln!(stderr(), ...)` is unaffected by `set_panic()` (just as `writeln!"
"(stdout(), ...)` is unaffected by `set_print()`).  This is arguably a bug.  "
"On the other hand, it is also arguably the Right Thing."
msgstr ""

